children.text: CSS Test: Scrolling Backgrounds in Scrolling Backgrounds
You should see teal underneath the dotted black border below.

rects.text: You should see teal underneath the dotted black border below.

children.text: There should be exactly two teal-bordered aqua rectangles visible inside the dotted border at all times, with yellow stripes above and below.

rects.text: There should be exactly two teal-bordered aqua rectangles visible inside the dotted border at all times, with yellow stripes above and below.

children.text: As you scroll the element below the teal, aqua, and yellow regions should not move.

rects.text: As you scroll the element below the teal, aqua, and yellow regions should not move.

children.text: However, as you scroll the aqua-and-teal element, a cat surrounded by an orange dotted border should come into view, with its own associated nested scrolling mechanism.

rects.text: However, as you scroll the aqua-and-teal element, a cat surrounded by an orange dotted border should come into view, with its own associated nested scrolling mechanism.

children.text: As you scroll the aqua-and-teal element, the cat should move up and down with its border.

rects.text: As you scroll the aqua-and-teal element, the cat should move up and down with its border.

children.text: As you scroll the numbers inside the orange border, the cat should not move.

rects.text: As you scroll the numbers inside the orange border, the cat should not move.

children.text: The aqua rectangles should be visible inside the dotted orange border.

rects.text: The aqua rectangles should be visible inside the dotted orange border.
